description: Ab Dekh Khuda Kia Karta Hai - Episode 20 Teaser | HAR PAL GEOAb Dekh Khuda Kiya Karta Hai, is based on the life of a fraudulent businessman Jan-e-Alam who manipulates young innocent girls who are chronically jobless, by giving them a job and subjecting them to improper advances. Many women working under Jan-e-Alam are constantly harassed, subjected to assaults, and slandered when they refuse the advances of their boss. Maryam, the female protagonist, also gets victimized by him. When she refuses to comply with his inappropriate demands, he traps her in a business scam and gets her jailed. Maryam manages to get herself out but unfortunately she keeps finding herself under the threat of her malicious ex employer who doesn‚Äôt seem to stop making her life miserable.  In a society, where it is so easy for a young girl to lose her dignity and to stain her reputation because of uncontrollable circumstances, will Maryam ever get riddance from sick minded Jan-e-Alam?Written by: Syed Ameer Ali Shah Hussaini Directed by: Syed Ali Raza UsamaProduced by: Babar JavedCast with respective character names: Danish Taimoor (Jaan-e-Alam), Sanam Chaudhry (Maryam), Humayoun Ashraf (Shaan-e-Alam), Qavi Khan (Naseer), Sajida Syed (Firdous), Rashid Farooqui (Malik), Parveen Akbar (Shaista), Yashma Gill (Noor Saba), Maryam Noor (Erum), Ali Rizvi (Hammad), Salah Uddin Tunio (Minister), Talat Iqbal (Ashfaq), Farzana Thaeem (Salma).For More Videos Subscribe YouTube - https://www.youtube.com/harpalgeo#ADKKKH#harpalgeo#GEO

Do not forget to like, share and subscribe.Ingredients:‚Ä¢ 2 tsp Oil‚Ä¢ 1/2 tsp Mustard seeds‚Ä¢ 1/2 tsp Cumin seeds‚Ä¢ 7~8 finely chopped Garlic cloves‚Ä¢ 8~10 Curry leaves‚Ä¢ 8~10 Fenugreek seeds‚Ä¢ A pinch of Hing‚Ä¢ 1/2 cup finely chopped Onion‚Ä¢ 1 tsp Goda masala‚Ä¢ 1 tsp Red chili powder‚Ä¢ 5 medium size chopped Tomatoes‚Ä¢ Salt to taste‚Ä¢ 1 tbsp Roasted peanut powder‚Ä¢ 1 tsp Jaggery‚Ä¢ Finely chopped Coriander leavesMethod:‚Ä¢ Heat up oil in a pan. ‚Ä¢ Add mustard seeds and let them pop up. ‚Ä¢ Add cumin seeds and let them crackle. ‚Ä¢ Add garlic, curry leaves, fenugreek seeds, a pinch of hing, onion   and mix well. ‚Ä¢ Fry on medium heat until it gets light golden color. ‚Ä¢ Add goda masala, red chili powder and mix well. ‚Ä¢ Fry for about a minute or two. ‚Ä¢ Add chopped tomatoes, salt to taste, and mix well. ‚Ä¢ Cover and cook on medium heat until tomatoes cook nice and   soft for about 5 minutes. ‚Ä¢ You can cook more if you want to make it puree. ‚Ä¢ Add roasted peanut powder, jaggery and mix well. ‚Ä¢ You can use sugar in place of jaggery. ‚Ä¢ Cook for 2-3 minutes more. ‚Ä¢ Add a lot of coriander leaves and mix well. ‚Ä¢ Tomato chutney or bhaji is already. ‚Ä¢ You can have this with fulka, chapatti. ‚Ä¢ It goes well with rice too.Subscribe to my other channelsMadharasrecipehttp://www.youtube.com/c/madhurasrecipe?sub_confirmation=1Hindi channelhttps://www.youtube.com/channel/UCIdtPLjTb111r4iubQ9Mq5A?sub_confirmation=1For more Such Recipes‡§¨‡§ü‡§æ‡§ü‡§Ø‡§æ‡§ö‡•Ä ‡§≠‡§æ‡§ú‡•Ä | Batata Bhaji | Aloo Sabzi | Aloo ki Sukhi Sabzi | madhurasrecipehttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wYI6DaVclAI&t=1s‡§∏‡•ã‡§™‡•ç‡§™‡•Ä ‡§´‡•ç‡§≤‡•â‡§µ‡§∞ ‡§¨‡§ü‡§æ‡§ü‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ‡§ö‡•Ä ‡§≠‡§æ‡§ú‡•Ä | Aloo Gobi Masala | Madhuras Recipes | Ep - description: Singhare ki Sabji Recipe , water chestnut curry,  Paniphar ki sabziIngredients:Water Chestnut - 400 gmsTomatoes - 2 (100 gms)Ginger - ¬Ω inch BatonGreen chilli - 2Mustard Oil - 2 tbspGreen Coriander - 2 to 3 tbsp (finely chopped)Asafoetida - ¬Ω pinch Cumin Seeds - ¬Ω tspTurmeric Powder - ¬Ω tspCoriander Powder - 1 TspRed chilli powder - ¬Ω tspGaram Masala - less than ¬º tspSalt - ¬æ tspChickpea Flour - 1 tbspHow to make Singhara Curry (Water Chestnut)For boiling Singhara1- Take 400 gms of Singhara after washing and drying them. 2- For the boiling process, add them in the pressure cooker along with 1 cup of water. 3- Turn on the flame, close lid of the cooker and boil until the first whistle arrive.4- Turn the flame to low after the first whistle and leave them to cook for more 2 minutes. 5- Switch off the flame after 3 minutes and wait until its pressure releases. 6- Drain the boiled Singharas out of the cooker and let them cool down.7- After cooling, peel the boiled Singharas using a knife. For the Curry 1- Preheat 2 tbsp of Mustard Oil, add ¬Ω tsp of Cumin Seeds on the low flame and roast it.2- Add ¬Ω pinch of Asafoetida, ¬Ω tsp of Turmeric Powder, 1 tsp of Coriander Powder and saute the spices.3- Prepare a paste of Tomatoes, Green Chillies and Ginger. 4- Add the paste in the sauteed spices along with ¬Ω tsp of Red chilli powder and cook while stirring it on the medium flame. 5- Roast the spices until Oil separates from it.6- Take a tempering pan and add 1-2 tbsp of Oil in it, add 1 tbsp of chickpea flour in it and roast while continuously stirring it until its colour changes. 7- Add the roasted chickpea flour in the masala mixture.8- Add the Boiled Singharas in the masala mixture along with ¬Ω tsp of Salt, less than ¬º tsp of Garam Masala, 2 to 3 tbsp of finely chopped Green coriander and roast while continuously stirring them for 2 minutes. 9- Add ¬Ω / 1 cup of water in it and cook while covering it for 5 minutes on the low flame. 10- The Singhara curry is ready to be served11- Garnish it with finely chopped Green Coriander.Serving:1- You can serve it with Chappati, Paratha, Naan or Rice.2- This amount of the curry is enough for the 3-4 members of a family. title: Best Street Food at Pakistan University - CRISIS OMELET in Islamabad | Pakistani Food Tour!
tags: Islamabad,Islamabad food,street food Pakistan,Pakistani food,Pakistani street food,Islamabad street food,Majeed Huts,Mark Wiens,Pakistan food,Pakistan cuisine,curry,street food videos,food videos,food vlogger,food blogger,things to do in Islamabad,what to do in Islamabad,mark wiens Islamabad,best of Islamabad,attractions Islamabad,islamabad serena hotel,best hotels islamabad
description: SUBSCRIBE http://bit.ly/MarkWiensSubscribe for 2 new videos every weekT-shirts and caps: https://goo.gl/6WdK1lThank you to Islamabad Serena Hotel for sponsoring my stay: https://goo.gl/M7iVDAThank you to Ali (Pakistan Travel Market): https://goo.gl/VY6NjHIslamabad is the capital city of Pakistan, and when you are there, you‚Äôll notice that it‚Äôs quite a bit more organized and spread out compared to many other major cities in Pakistan. We only had one full day in Islamabad, and we decided to make the most of it by going to a few of the top street food stall and restaurants that I wanted to check out. It turned out to be an amazing day of Pakistan food in Islamabad!Islamabad Serena Hotel - First of all, we were hosted at Islamabad Serena Hotel, an amazing hotel in Islamabad. The rooms were great, it‚Äôs a huge hotel, and the breakfast buffet was extensive and very good. We woke up in the morning and headed straight for breakfast.Majeed Huts (https://goo.gl/maps/2XyimxWyBcH2) - After reading about Majeed Huts in Roads and Kingdoms years ago, I knew it was a place I wanted to go. We went straight for Majeed Huts, which is a local Pakistani food dhaba, hole in the wall restaurant, on a university campus. Along with a multitude of Pakistani curries and dishes, one of their signature dishes is their ‚Äúcrisis‚Äù omelet, a combination of all the leftovers, mixed up, and filled into an oily omelet. It will solve any crisis, it‚Äôs that good. The rest of the food was equally as impressive, and I loved the atmosphere. Majeed Huts dhaba in Islamabad is one of my personal favorite restaurants from my entire trip to Pakistan.Total price - 1,900 PKR ($14.21) for everythingThe Monal - When we were in Islamabad we had to run a few errands in the afternoon, and things go late, so we didn‚Äôt make it up to Monal until dusk. Anyway, it was still a great view. They have a famous restaurant, but we only went for the view.Afghani Kabab House - For dinner number 1, Ali and I went to Afghani Kabab House, a local favorite serving Afghani kebabs grilled up in a cloud of smoke. While there, we met a group of guys who watch our videos, and they invited us to eat with them. The kebabs are amazing, and I also really enjoyed the Kabuli pulao. Again, another street food stall in Islamabad that you can‚Äôt miss, it‚Äôs amazing.Dawat Restaurant - Finally, Joel and I were invited to Dawat Restaurant, the Pakistani food restaurant at Islamabad Serena Hotel for second dinner. It was a nice restaurant, and really good, really tender meat. The biryani in particular stood out to me, as did the shrimp pakoras.Again, this was my only full day in Islamabad, but it was an amazing day!Ali: https://goo.gl/VY6NjHJoel: https://goo.gl/5AkWm6MUSIC: https://us.audionetwork.com/Logo: https://goo.gl/VhaLp5CAMERA GEAR I used to make this video (these are affiliate links):Main camera: http://amzn.to/2sV0XQOMain lens: http://amzn.to/2szLZNf2nd lens: http://amzn.to/2EjBeEgMicrophone: http://amzn.to/2rBKD3zDrone: http://amzn.to/2CrtAHzFOLLOW:Instagram: https://instagram.com/migrationologyFacebook: https://www.facebook.com/migrationologyThank you for watching!

title: Very beautiful small rangoli art designs by Suneetha || easy n simple kolam || latest cute muggulu
tags: rangoli,rangoli designs,kolam,kolam designs,muggulu,muggulu designs,rangoli with dots,rangoli designs with dots,easy rangoli,easy rangoli designs,rangoli art,rangoli art designs,rangoli kolam,kolam rangoli,kolam with dots,kolam designs with dots,simple kolam,sikku kolam,padi kolam,easy kolam,muggulu with dots,muggulu designs with dots,chukkala muggulu,melika muggulu,designs,designs with dots,how to draw,latest rangoli,indian art,indian rangoli
description: It is our tradition to draw kolam every day morning at the door steps.There are many benifits of drawing kolam in front of the house.It is auspecious and believes Godess Lakshmi enters the house if kolam is drawn.Kolam brings lot of positive vibrations and energy to you and your home.Draw kolam soon after you wake up and then do your prayers.Kolam or rangoli is a part of Indian culture and transferred from generation to next generation.This ancient art form is also called as muggulu in parts  of South India like Andhra pradesh and Telangana.People draw different creative rangoli kolam designs using kolam powder or muggu pindi which is actually crushed Lime stone powder available at different parts of India.There are different types of rangoli or kolam designs like dots kolam, sikku kolam, padi kolam, Margazhi kolam.People draw special rangoli designs for Festivals like Sankranthi (Pongal), Diwali (Deepavali), Vijaya dasami (Dasara).Women create deepam rangoli or kolam designs during diwali festival time, create very big and Dhanurmasam muggulu (Margazhi) for Sankranthi or Pongal festival.It is a belief among the people that drawing muggulu infront of the house in the early morning soon after wake bringsgood fortune to them and their family.People mix rice flour to lime stone powder and prepare their own kolam powder. Muggulu can also be drawn with rice flour only.These Beautiful and creative designs are decorated with flowers based on the occasion or festival.

description: oil will separate and the halwa will not stick to the pan ,that sholud be the consistency of the halwaIngredients:Maida / All purpose flour ‚Äì 2 cupsNuts of your choice (I used cashew nuts and pumpkin seeds)Sugar ‚Äì 2¬Ω cupsFood colour ‚Äì ¬º tsp (I used orange colour)Coconut oil / Sunflower oil ‚Äì 3¬Ω cupsSteps:Add 10 cups of water to 2 cups of maida and mix well.Leave it covered for 2 days to ferment.Strain and discard the solids.Heat a pan and add 2 cups of water.Add food colour and mix well.Add half of the sugar to the pan.Let it melt.Once the water boils, add 1¬º cup oil.Add the maida mixture.Keep stirring continuously.Once it starts to thicken, add 1¬Ω cup oil and mix well.Add the remaining sugar.Reduce the flame when you add oil.Then increase the flame and keep stirring.Add 1 cup oil.When oil starts to separate, add nuts.Cook stirring for another ¬Ω hour.Remember to stir the whole time.Switch off once the mixture thickens well.It took me around 2 hours to get the halwa done.Remove the excess oil using a dry utensil.Add some nuts to a cake tin/pan.Transfer the hot mixture to the pan.Smoothen the surface.Let it cool.Invert and cut the Kozhikode halwa.It tastes better after a couple of days.More halwa recipes:Black Halwa with rice flour -
